interpretation_text:
The patient’s CGM data demonstrates suboptimal glycemic control, with a mean glucose of 208 mg/dL, GMI of 8.29%, and only 21% time in range. Glycemic variability is markedly elevated (CV 58.4%, SD 121.5 mg/dL). There is significant hyperglycemia (57% time >180 mg/dL), frequent hypoglycemia (22% time <70 mg/dL, 10 events, including 1 nocturnal), and pronounced postprandial excursions (371 spikes). Dawn phenomenon is present.

Abnormal patterns include frequent and severe glycemic excursions, both hyper- and hypoglycemia, significant postprandial spikes, and a nocturnal hypoglycemia event. Dawn phenomenon suggests early morning hyperglycemia.

Recommendations: Intensify glucose management to increase time in range and reduce variability. Review and adjust overnight basal insulin to minimize nocturnal and overall hypoglycemia. Assess patient’s hypoglycemia awareness and carbohydrate counting accuracy. Address postprandial hyperglycemia by evaluating bolus timing/dosing and meal composition. Consider adjusting basal insulin timing or splitting doses to address dawn phenomenon. Close follow-up and possible diabetes education are indicated.
